The issues come in the mixed type cases. Consider this C program:<p><pre><code>    #include <stdio.h>

    int main(void) {
        long   x = 9007199254740992;    // 2^53
        double y = 9007199254740992.0;  // 2.0^53
        long   z = 9007199254740993;    // 2^53+1
        printf(&quot;x == y: %d\n&quot;, x == y);
        printf(&quot;y == z: %d\n&quot;, y == z);
        printf(&quot;x == z: %d\n&quot;, x == z);
        return 0;
    }
</code></pre>
Its output shows that &quot;==&quot; is not transitive in C:<p><pre><code>    x == y: 1
    y == z: 1
    x == z: 0
</code></pre>
On the other hand, &quot;==&quot; is transitive in Julia:<p><pre><code>    julia> x, y, z = 9007199254740992, 9007199254740992.0, 9007199254740993;

    julia> x == y, y == z, x == z
    (true,false,false)
</code></pre>
You have to be careful: if you compare &quot;y&quot; and &quot;z&quot; by converting &quot;z&quot; to Float64, they appear to be equal even though they represent entirely different integer values. When subtracting them, however, one does convert them to Float64, so their difference is zero:<p><pre><code>    julia> z - y
    0.0
</code></pre>
This kind of issue is why it&#x27;s so important to have a theory of what &quot;==&quot; means.
